and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert FitzWilliam de Cardinham was born on 1 January 1115, in Cotleigh, Devon, England, his father, William FitzRichard Lord of Cardinham, was 31 and his mother, Annora de Mortaigne of Cornwall, was 29. He married Annora \"Agnes\" de Mandeville in United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1177, in Bodmin, Cornwall, England, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1 January 1115–1177":"1. jaanuar 1115–1177","1115–1177":"1115–1177","1115–1162":"1115–1162","–1169":"–1169","–Female":"Surnud","1120–1169":"1120–1169","1145–1186":"1145–1186","1084–1136":"1084–1136","1086–1130":"1086–1130","1186":"1186","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1162":"1162","1084":"1084","1 January 1115":"1. jaanuar 1115","1115":"1115","1136":"1136","1169":"1169","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1177":"1177","after 1169":"pärast 1169","Cotleigh, Devon, England":"Cotleigh, Devon, England","Cardinham Castle, Cardinham, Bodmin, Cornwall, England":"Cardinham, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cardinham, Cornwall, England":"Cardinham, Cornwall, England","United Ki